Diagnostic sensitivity and specificity was determined by testing EFS by both Chelex method and FTA method of DNA extraction followed by real-time PCR. A total of 316 EFS batches were tested and the diagnostic sensitivity and specificity of the FTA method with respect to Chelex method was found to be 83.08% (95% CI: 71.73%–91.24%) and 93.23% (95% CI: 89.38%–96.01%) respectively (Table 1
). The Positive Predictive Value was 76.06% (95% CI: 64.46%–85.39%) and Negative Predictive Value 95.51% (95% CI: 92.11%–97.74%). The degree of agreement between the two tests was found to be good (kappa value: 0.738; 95% CI: 0.646–0.829). The range of Ct values obtained for the positive clinical samples in Chelex and FTA methods are presented in Table 2
.
